const faqs = [
  { q: "Is it legal to take direct bookings instead of using Airbnb?", a: "Yes, completely legal. You're free to rent your property to guests through any channel, including your own website. The same municipal bylaws apply regardless of whether guests find you on Airbnb or your personal site. You still need an STR license (where required), must collect MAT, and follow all local regulations." },
  { q: "How much does it cost to build a direct booking website?", a: "Anywhere from $0 to $100/month depending on your approach. A basic Carrd or WordPress site costs under $20/month. Dedicated hospitality platforms like Lodgify or Hospitable run $30 to $80/month but include channel management, payment processing, and automated messaging. Most hosts start with a simple one-page site and upgrade as direct bookings grow." },
  { q: "How do I handle payment processing for direct bookings?", a: "Stripe is the most popular option for Canadian hosts. It charges 2.9% + $0.30 per transaction, which is still far less than Airbnb's 14-20% combined fees. Square and PayPal are alternatives. Most hospitality booking platforms (Lodgify, Hostaway) include built-in payment processing through Stripe integration." },
  { q: "Do I lose Airbnb's insurance when I take direct bookings?", a: "Yes. AirCover only applies to bookings made through Airbnb. For direct bookings, you need your own short-term rental insurance policy. Canadian options include Duuo (pay-per-night), APOLLO, and Square One. A typical policy costs $3 to $8 per booked night, which is still cheaper than what you save on Airbnb fees." },
  { q: "How do I screen guests without Airbnb's review system?", a: "Use third-party guest screening tools like Autohost, Guest Ranger, or Superhog. These services verify government ID, run background checks, and assess risk. Many hosts also require a signed rental agreement, a security deposit, and a brief phone call before confirming any direct booking." },
